8 Be It Enacted by the Legislature of the State of Idaho:
9 SECTION 1. That the Heading for Chapter 5, Title 73, Idaho Code, be, and
10 the same is hereby amended to read as follows:
11 CHAPTER 5
12 CORONAVIRUS STOP IDAHO MEDICAL FREEDOM ACT
13 SECTION 2. That Section 73-501, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
14 amended to read as follows:
15 73-501. SHORT TITLE. This chapter shall be known and may be cited as
16 the "Coronavirus Stop Idaho Medical Freedom Act."
17 SECTION 3. That Section 73-502, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
18 amended to read as follows:
19 73-502. DEFINITIONS. As used in this chapter:
20 (1) "Business entity" means any person or group of persons performing
21 or engaging in any activity, enterprise, profession, or occupation for gain,
22 benefit, advantage, or livelihood, whether for profit or not-for-profit,
23 except for any daycare, daycare center, daycare facility, family daycare
24 home, or group daycare facility as defined in section 39-1102, Idaho Code.
25 "Business entity" shall include but not be limited to:
26 (a) Self-employed individuals, business entities filing articles of
27 incorporation, partnerships, limited partnerships, limited liability
28 companies, foreign corporations, foreign limited partnerships, for-
29 eign limited liability companies authorized to transact business in
30 Idaho, business trusts, and any business entity that registers with the
31 secretary of state; and
32 (b) Any business entity that possesses a business license, permit, cer-
33 tificate, approval, registration, charter, or similar form of autho-
34 rization issued by the state; any business entity exempt by law from ob-
35 taining such a business license; and any business entity operating un-
36 lawfully without such a business license.
37 (2) "Coronavirus" means:
38 (a) Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2;

2
1 (b) The disease caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coron-
2 avirus 2; or
3 (c) Any subsequently identified mutation, modification, or strain of
4 severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 if the transmission of
5 said virus among humans rises to the level of an epidemic or pandemic and
6 qualifies for an emergency declaration under applicable Idaho law.
7 (3) "Coronavirus vaccination" means the introduction of a coronavirus
8 vaccine into the human body.
9 (4) (2) "Foreign jurisdiction" means any state, commonwealth, country,
10 or nation outside the state of Idaho.
11 (3) "Medical intervention" means a medical procedure, treatment, de-
12 vice, drug injection, medication, or medical action taken to diagnose, pre-
13 vent, or cure a disease or alter the health or biological function of a per-
14 son.
15 (4) "School" means any public, private, or parochial preschool; any
16 kindergarten, elementary, or secondary school; any postsecondary institute
17 of education, including trade schools, colleges, and universities; or any
18 other institute of primary, secondary, or higher learning operating in this
19 state.
20 (5) "Ticket issuer" means an individual or entity providing tickets to
21 an entertainment event, including any of the following:
22 (a) The operator of the venue where an entertainment event occurs;
23 (b) The sponsor or promoter of an entertainment event;
24 (c) A sports team participating in an entertainment event or a league
25 whose teams are participating in an entertainment event;
26 (d) A theater company, musical group, or similar participant in an en-
27 tertainment event; or
28 (e) An agent of any individual or entity described in this subsection.
29 SECTION 4. That Section 73-503, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
30 amended to read as follows:
31 73-503. CORONAVIRUS VACCINATION REQUIREMENTS MEDICAL MANDATES PRO-
32 HIBITED. (1) A business entity doing business in the state of Idaho shall not
33 refuse to provide any service, product, admission to a venue, or transporta-
34 tion to a person because that person has or has not received a coronavirus
35 vaccination or used a medical intervention.
36 (2) A business entity doing business in the state of Idaho shall not
37 require a coronavirus vaccination medical intervention as a term of em-
38 ployment unless required by federal law or in such cases where the terms of
39 employment include travel to foreign jurisdictions requiring coronavirus
40 vaccinations a medical intervention as the only coronavirus-related means
41 of entry or where the terms of employment require entry into a place of
42 business or facility in a foreign jurisdiction and such place of business
43 or facility requires a coronavirus vaccination medical intervention as the
44 only coronavirus-related means of entry. In any such instance where an
45 employee is required to obtain or use a coronavirus vaccination medical in-
46 tervention due to travel to a foreign jurisdiction or entry into a place of
47 business or facility in a foreign jurisdiction, said requirement shall ei-
48 ther be included in a valid written employment contract between the employer
49 and the employee or, when a written employment contract does not exist, ad-

3
1 vance written notice shall be provided to an impacted employee no less than
2 fourteen (14) days prior to such employee being required to receive or use a
3 coronavirus vaccination medical intervention. Business entities that re-
4 ceive medicare or medicaid funding shall be exempt from the requirements of
5 this subsection.
6 (3) A ticket issuer shall not penalize, discriminate against, or deny
7 access to an entertainment event to a ticket holder because the ticket holder
8 has or has not received or used a coronavirus vaccination medical interven-
9 tion.
10 (4) A school operating in the state shall not mandate a medical inter-
11 vention for any person to attend school, enter campus or school buildings, or
12 be employed by the school, subject to the requirements of the Idaho parental
13 rights act, sections 32-1010 through 32-1015, Idaho Code; sections 39-4801
14 through 39-4804, Idaho Code; and sections 33-205 and 33-512(7), Idaho Code.
15 (4) (5) Unless required by federal law, no state, county, or local gov-
16 ernment entity or official in Idaho shall require any person to receive or
17 use a coronavirus vaccination medical intervention.
18 (5) (6) Unless required by federal law, no state, county, or local gov-
19 ernment entity or official in Idaho shall require any person to receive or
20 use a coronavirus vaccination medical intervention as a condition for:
21 (a) Receipt of any government benefit;
22 (b) Receipt of any government services;
23 (c) Receipt of any government-issued license or permit;
24 (d) Entrance into any public building;
25 (e) Use of public transportation; or
26 (f) A term of employment, provided that such entities that receive
27 medicare or medicaid funding shall be exempt from the requirements of
28 this paragraph.
29 (6) (7) No state, county, or local government, or business entity in
30 Idaho shall provide or offer any different salary, hourly wage, or other on-
31 going compensation or benefits to an employee based on whether the employee
32 has or has not received or used a coronavirus vaccination medical interven-
33 tion. However, it shall not be unlawful for such entities to offer onetime
34 incentives related to coronavirus vaccinations that do not result in any
35 different salary, hourly wage, or ongoing compensation or benefits being
36 provided to an employee based on whether they have or have not received a
37 coronavirus vaccination. A business entity may permit its employees to be
38 released from work for the purpose of receiving a coronavirus vaccination.
39 (7) (8) The ability to require a coronavirus vaccination medical inter-
40 vention under this chapter is subject to other statutory or constitutional
41 provisions regarding requests for coronavirus vaccination exemptions
42 medical interventions and requirements to provide reasonable accommoda-
43 tion.
44 (9) The prohibition on medical interventions shall not apply to any
45 situation where personal protective equipment, items, or clothing are
46 required by a business entity in the public or private sectors based on ex-
47 isting traditional and accepted industry standards or federal law. These
48 exemptions to the prohibition on medical interventions shall not apply to
49 or include any vaccines, mask requirements, or other medical interventions
50 introduced during the COVID-19 pandemic.

